a.xlink:title: The AdditionalData class serves as an extension mechanism for information not otherwise represented in the data model. For relatively simple information, atomic data types (e.g., integers, strings) are provided with a mechanism to annotate their meaning. The class can also be used to extend the data model (and the associated Schema) to support proprietary extensions by encapsulating entire XML documents conforming to another Schema (e.g., IDMEF). A detailed discussion for extending the data model and the schema can be found in Section 5.

This attribute has been defined in Section 3.2.

The EventData class describes a particular event of the incident for a given set of hosts or networks. This description includes the systems from which the activity originated and those targeted, an assessment of the techniques used by the intruder, the impact of the activity on the organization, and any forensic evidence discovered.
The time the event was detected.
A free-form textual description of the event.
The time the event started.
The time the event ended.
This attribute is defined in Section 3.2.
The Flow class groups related the source and target hosts.

The Contact class describes contact information for organizations and personnel involved in the incident. This class allows for the naming of the involved party, specifying contact information for them, and identifying their role in the incident.
The facsimile telephone number of the contact.
A free-form description of this contact. In the case of a person, this is often the organizational title of the individual.
The telephone number of the contact.
The name of the contact. The contact may either be an organization or a person. The type attribute disambiguates the semantics.
The timezone in which the contact resides formatted according to Section 2.9.

The Expectation class conveys to the recipient of the IODEF document the actions the sender is requesting. The scope of the requested action is limited to purview of the EventData class in which this class is aggregated.
The time by which the action should be completed. If the action is not carried out by this time, it should no longer be performed.
A free-form description of the desired action(s).

The time at which the action should be performed. A timestamp that is earlier than the ReportTime specified in the Incident class denotes that the expectation should be fulfilled as soon as possible. The absence of this element leaves the execution of the expectation to the discretion of the recipient.
Classifies the type of action requested. This attribute is an enumerated list with no default value.
This attribute is defined in Section 3.2.
A means by which to extend the action attribute. See Section 5.1.
Indicates the desired priority of the action. This attribute is an enumerated list with no default value, and the semantics of these relative measures are context dependent.

The Record class is a container class for log and audit data that provides supportive information about the incident. The source of this data will often be the output of monitoring tools. These logs should substantiate the activity described in the document.
This attribute has been defined in Section 3.2.
The Assessment class describes the technical and non-technical repercussions of the incident on the CSIRT's constituency.
This attribute is defined in Section 3.2.
Specifies whether the assessment is describing actual or potential outcomes. The default is "actual" and is assumed if not specified.

The Method class describes the methodology used by the intruder to perpetrate the events of the incident. This class consists of a list of references describing the attack method and a free form description of the technique.
A free-form text description of the methodology used by the intruder.
This attribute is defined in Section 3.2.
The NodeRole class describes the intended function performed by a particular host.
Functionality provided by a node.
A valid language code per RFC 4646 [7] constrained by the definition of "xs:language". The interpretation of this code is described in Section 6.
A means by which to extend the category attribute. See Section 5.1.
The Node class names a system (e.g., PC, router) or network.
A free-from description of the physical location of the equipment.
The name of the Node (e.g., fully qualified domain name). This information MUST be provided if no Address information is given.
A timestamp of when the resolution between the name and address was performed. This information SHOULD be provided if both an Address and NodeName are specified.
The Address class represents a hardware (layer-2), network (layer-3), or application (layer-7) address.
The type of address represented. The permitted values for this attribute are shown below. The default value is "ipv4-addr".
The name of the Virtual LAN to which the address belongs.
A means by which to extend the category attribute. See Section 5.1.
The number of the Virtual LAN to which the address belongs.
The Counter class summarize multiple occurrences of some event, or conveys counts or rates on various features (e.g., packets, sessions, events).

If present, the Counter class represents a rate rather than a count over the entire event. In that case, this attribute specifies the denominator of the rate (where the type attribute specified the nominator). The possible values of this attribute are defined in Section 3.10.2
Specifies the units of the element content.
A means by which to extend the type attribute. See Section 5.1.
A means by which to extend the duration attribute. See Section 5.1.

The System class describes a system or network involved in an event. The systems or networks represented by this class are categorized according to the role they played in the incident through the category attribute. The value of this category attribute dictates the semantics of the aggregated classes in the System class. If the category attribute has a value of "source", then the aggregated classes denote the machine and service from which the activity is originating. With a category attribute value of "target" or "intermediary", then the machine or service is the one targeted in the activity. A value of "sensor" dictates that this System was part of an instrumentation to monitor the network.
A free-form text description of the System.
Classifies the role the host or network played in the incident. The possible values are:
This attribute is defined in Section 3.2.
A means by which to extend the category attribute. See Section 5.1.
An indication of confidence in whether this System was the true target or attacking host. The permitted values for this attribute are shown below. The default value is "unknown".
Specifies the interface on which the event(s) on this System originated. If the Node class specifies a network rather than a host, this attribute has no meaning.
The Service class describes a network service of a host or network. The service is identified by specific port or list of ports, along with the application listening on that port.

A layer-4 protocol specific type field (e.g., ICMP type field).
A port number.
The IANA protocol number.

The Email class specifies an email address formatted according to EMAIL data type (Section 2.14).

The RegistryHandle class represents a handle into an Internet registry or community-specific database. The handle is specified in the element content and the type attribute specifies the database.

A means by which to extend the registry attribute. See Section 5.1.
The RecordData class groups log or audit data from a given sensor (e.g., IDS, firewall log) and provides a way to annotate the output.
Free-form textual description of the provided RecordItem data. At minimum, this description should convey the significance of the provided RecordItem data.
Timestamp of the RecordItem data.
This attribute has been defined in Section 3.2.

The RecordItem class provides a way to incorporate relevant logs, audit trails, or forensic data to support the conclusions made during the course of analyzing the incident. The class supports both the direct encapsulation of the data, as well as, provides primitives to reference data stored elsewhere.
The data type of the element content. The permitted values for this attribute are shown below. The default value is "string".
A free-form description of the element content.
A means by which to extend the dtype attribute. See Section 5.1.
An identifier referencing the format and semantics of the element content.
This attribute has been defined in Section 3.2.

The RecordPattern class describes where in the content of the RecordItem relevant information can be found. It provides a way to reference subsets of information, identified by a pattern, in a large log file, audit trail, or forensic data.
Number of types to apply the specified pattern.
A means by which to extend the type attribute. See Section 5.1.
Amount of units (determined by the offsetunit attribute) to seek into the RecordItem data before matching the pattern.
Describes the units of the offset attribute. The default is "line".
A means by which to extend the offsetunit attribute. See Section 5.1.
Describes the type of pattern being specified in the element content. The default is "regex".
The Impact class allows for categorizing and describing the technical impact of the incident on the network of an organization.
A valid language code per RFC 4646 [7] constrained by the definition of "xs:language". The interpretation of this code is described in Section 6.
An indication whether the described activity was successful. The permitted values are shown below. There is no default value.
Classifies the malicious activity into incident categories. The permitted values are shown below. The default value is "other".
An estimate of the relative severity of the activity. The permitted values are shown below. There is no default value.
A means by which to extend the type attribute. See Section 5.1.

The Confidence class represents a best estimate of the validity and accuracy of the described impact (see Section 3.10) of the incident activity. This estimate can be expressed as a category or a numeric calculation.
A rating of the analytical validity of the specified Assessment. The permitted values are shown below. There is no default value.
The TimeImpact class describes the impact of the incident on an organization as a function of time. It provides a way to convey down time and recovery time.
A means by which to extend the metric attribute. See Section 5.1.

Defines a unit of time, that when combined with the metric attribute, fully describes a metric of impact that will be conveyed in the element content. The permitted values are shown below. The default value is "hour".
Defines the metric in which the time is expressed. The permitted values are shown below. There is no default value.
An estimate of the relative severity of the activity. The permitted values are shown below. There is no default value.
A means by which to extend the duration attribute. See Section 5.1.

The Reference class is a reference to a vulnerability, IDS alert, malware sample, advisory, or attack technique. A reference consists of a name, a URL to this reference, and an optional description.
A URL associated with the reference.
